{
  "answer": "**Manu’s *Manusmṛti* (Book 1) links the origin of the *kṣatriya* (and other *varṇas*) to cosmogony as follows:**\n\nFor the prosperity of the worlds, the Self-existent One causes the Brahmin, Kshatriya, Vaiśya, and Śudra to proceed from his mouth, arms (*bāhu*, i.e., arms for the Kshatriya), thighs, and feet.[^1] He then assigns distinct duties to those who proceed from these body parts: protection of the people (for the Kshatriya), alongside study, sacrifice, gifts, and detachment from sense-objects.[^2]\n\n**Charles Comte’s *Traité de Législation* (Vol. II, Book 2, Ch. 2) does not explicitly link \"aristocracy\" to \"modes of existence,\" despite targeted searches across the corpus (including phrases like \"aristocracy\" + \"modes of existence\"/\"mode of existence\"/\"existence,\" and broader variants). The closest passages discuss aristocracy in relation to human *species* differences (physical organization, climate), which shape capacities for perfection and \"considerably influence the existence\" of societies (e.g., republics).** \n\nComte observes that traditional aristocracies involved classes of the *same species*, but colonial contexts introduced an \"aristocracy of species,\" where Europeans deem non-Caucasian varieties (copper-colored/American, Ethiopian, Malay) inferior in physical/intellectual development—used to justify slavery—and predicts this will shape republics' futures.[^3] He rejects equal perfectibility across varieties, tying social hierarchies to innate physical differences (contra Helvétius).[^4]\n\n**Both texts map social structure onto \"material conditions,\" but Manu's is cosmogonic (divine body as primal matter), while Comte's is biological (racial/species physiology).** Manu's embeds hierarchy in sacred creation and *dharma* duties, reiterated in ritual/recitation; Comte's is secular/Enlightenment analysis of empirical varieties, open to refutation by later science (e.g., genetics/climatology). The corpus lacks direct comparison of \"metaphysical depths,\" but Manu's mythic-religious rooting—tied to eternal *yugas*, *tapas*, and *śruti*—appears harder to dislodge than Comte's contingent racialism, as the former sacralizes inequality as cosmic order while the latter rationalizes it as observable (and revisable) fact.\n\n[^1]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-13a2db).\n[^2]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-f0b26c).\n[^3]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL II*, [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-ii-20331d/02-des-limites-mises-par-la-nature-au-perfectionnemen/translation/#p-44e2ce).\n[^4]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL II*, [paragraphs](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-ii-20331d/02-des-limites-mises-par-la-nature-au-perfectionnemen/translation/#p-991516).",
